text:
techTFQ - the main difference between delete and truncate statements besides removing the data from the table, truncate resets the id to 0 whereas delete doesn't do that. let's say if a table has 100 records. if you use delete statement and delete all 100 records and try to insert a new record. Your new record will have the id starting from 101 whereas with truncate it will start from 1. I think this isn't on your differences. Basically, truncate removes the memory allocation along with the data whereas delete doesn't.

Thanks!

text:
SQL syntax will be the same across PostgreSQL and sql server..

The only difference will be in functions like date format functions or substring kind of functions‚Ä¶

But if you learn sql using any rdbms , you will still be able to apply all that knowledge to any other rdbms..

I started my career with oracle and used oracle for 8 years straight and then I joined a company where they were using SQL server, I think it just took me couple of days to get the hang of difference in sql server ..

And again after 2 years I one day started using PostgreSQL and it hardly took me any time to work on Postgres..

So just want to say, it does not matter which rdbms u use to learn sql,
Once you understand sql, you will be able to work on any rdbms whether it sql server or MySQL or oracle or PostgreSQL..

text:
Great video as usual. I am your 10% of your subscribers :).
I have question regarding basics group by
what happens when you use distinct with group by. How the output will change. 
My understanding is group will group all the similar things together and distinct will just get the duplicates. Given a scenario below
Have a table Emp but it has duplicates as no PK define.
EMPID  Expense 
1              10
1              9
2             1
2             1
Now I am trying to get the minimum salary will the below query:-
select   EMPID  ,min(Expense ) from customer group by EMPID  
What will change If i write this as below 
select   EMPID  ,min(Expense ) from customer group by EMPID  
I tried to run the query both of them has the same output. Help me to understand better. How group by is working as nothing will change in both query output
2. Why it is so if you mention the column name in aggregate function you don't have to mention to mention the column name but if you mention without agg funcn it will look for group by column.
example
select   EMPID  ,min(Expense ) from customer group by EMPID   will work
but
select   EMPID  ,Expense ,min(Expense ) from customer group by EMPID  will not work and can mess up your output.
